    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 1,
      "text": "DTC Commentary: P1899"
    },
    {
      "type": "dtc",
      "code": "P1899",
      "text": "DTC P1899: Drive pulley control SOL.V. OFF stuck or driven pulley control SOL.V. ON stuck"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Detection principle explanation"
    },
    {
      "type": "figure",
      "asset": "145_3.0_jpn_11033686_4.0_disp.png"
    },
    {
      "type": "figure",
      "asset": "145_3.0_jpn_11033687_4.0_disp.png"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "The drive pulley control SOL.V. and driven pulley control SOL.V. control the hydraulic pressure in the hydraulic circuit. The spools in the drive pulley control SOL.V. and driven pulley control SOL.V. push valves in response to duty (load) outputs converted to current values by the PGM-FI ECU. As a result, the valve pushed by the spool releases oil pressure proportional to the current value. The PGM-FI ECU measures the current flowing in the linear solenoids of the drive pulley control SOL.V. and driven pulley control SOL.V., and feeds back control of the resulting difference compared to the command current at the duty output. The PGM-FI ECU outputs a control signal for drive/driven pulley hydraulic pressure for proper gear shifting. If the pulley ratio is overdrive when the vehicle is in gear (driving force transmission state) and the estimated input torque at start is less than the predetermined value and no belt slip occurs in the running state, the PGM-FI ECU judges that the drive pulley control SOL.V. is stuck at OFF or the driven pulley control SOL. V. and store the DTC."
    },
